-- Banks peg back UK FTSE after reduced tax allowance announced
-- By Alistair Smout and Sudip Kar-Gupta
-- Wed Dec 03, 2014 08:14AM EST
-- None



LONDON, Dec 3 (Reuters) - Britain's blue-chip index extended its losses in afternoon trade on Wednesday, led lower by the banking sector after the UK government announced a tightening of tax rules in the sector.

Shares fell after UK finance minister George Osborne said there would be reduced tax allowances for banks. This will raise 4 billion pounds ($6.27 billion) over next five years, Osborne added. The FTSE 350 Banking Index <.FTNMX8350> extended losses and was down by 0.6 percent by 1305 GMT. Barclays <BARC.L> was down by 1.4 percent, Lloyds <LLOY.L> fell 0.3 percent and Royal Bank of Scotland <RBS.L> was down by around 1 percent. Britain's FTSE 100 <.FTSE> was down 0.3 percent at 6,719.62 points at 1309 GMT.